Acyl-CoA dependent anthocyanin acyltransferases (ATs) belong to the BAHD AT family (
) and catalyze the specific transfer of an acyl group to the glucose moiety of anthocyanins, contributing to the structural diversity of anthocyanins. Anthocyanins are a class of flavonoids and major floral pigments that confer red and blue colors (
). The aromatic acylation of anthocyanins shifts their color to blue, and thus aromatic AT can be a useful molecular tool to modify flower color. The blue color of gentian (
Gentiana triflora Pall.
( Gentianaceae )) is derived from gentiodelphin (delphinidin 3- O -β- D- glucoside 5- O -(6

- O -caffeoyl-β- D- glucoside) 3 ′ - O -(6- O -caffeoyl-β- D- glucoside), where the 3 ′ -caffeoyl residue contributes to the production of a bluer color than the 5-caffeoyl residue (
). The gene encoding gentian hydroxycinnamoyl-CoA:anthocyanidin 3,5-diglucoside 5- O -glucoside-6 ′ - O -hydroxycinnamoyltransferase (Gt5 AT ) was isolated for the first time as an anthocyanin AT gene (
). Gt5 AT was later shown to catalyze acylation of 3 ′ -glucoside of anthocyanidin 3,5,3 ′ -triglucoside following the acylation of 5-glucoside, and was accordingly renamed Gt5,3 ′ AT (
) ( Fig. 1 ). Gt5,3 ′ AT has been shown to utilize caffeoyl-CoA and coumaroyl-CoA, but not aliphatic CoAs, such as malonyl-CoA, as an acyl donor (
, resolution of 2.2–1.8 Å (
). Malonyl-CoA (acyl donor) and anthocyanin (acyl acceptor) binding sites were identified in Dm3MAT3, where the latter was found to be different from that of vinorine synthase, another BAHD AT (
). These structures indicated that the acyl-CoA binding sites share structural similarities in their acceptance of common acyl-CoA (malonyl-CoA), whereas the structure of the acyl acceptor moieties can be adapted for individual ligands. In general, BAHD ATs share sequence similarities and conserved motifs, including HxxxD and DFGWG motifs, which play an important role in catalytic reactions (
). The ligand specificity of BAHD ATs can be investigated in two ways: (1) acyl-CoA recognition as a common binding mechanism and (2) anthocyanin recognition as diverse acyl acceptors. Structural analysis would provide critical information for understanding the molecular mechanisms underlying ligand recognition specificities.

