Eustoma grandiflorum (Raf.)Shinn.
( Gentianaceae )),which belongs to the same family as gentian ( Gentianaceae ), produces purple flowers, which mainly accumulate delphinidin 3-rhamnosylgalactoside 5- p -coumaroylglucoside (
). The acylation of 5-glucoside is catalyzed by lisianthus 5 AT (Eg5 AT ), and its cDNA and Eg5 AT cDNA has been isolated (GenBank accession no.AB078964.1).Anthocyanin ATs are regiospecific, that is, they usually catalyze the acylation of one glucose moiety at specific positions of anthocyanins, and their genes diversified after speciation of plant families, unlike the other flavonoid biosynthetic genes (
). Gt5,3 ′ AT and Eg5 AT are homologous and share 69% amino acid sequence identity. Although the substrate specificity of Eg5 AT has not been published, differences in the anthocyanins accumulated in gentian and lisianthus indicate that Gt5,3 ′ AT and Eg5 AT have distinctive enzymatic specificities. Therefore, structural insights are needed to understand how Gt5,3 ′ AT transfers acyl groups to the two anthocyanin positions. Furthermore, Gt5,3 ′ AT is the only so-far characterized BAHD type AT that catalyzes the acylation of the 3 ′ -glucoside of anthocyanins.

